Introduction
The Banking Fraud Detection & Customer Analytics project is a comprehensive SQL-based data analytics solution developed to simulate real-world banking operations and demonstrate practical database management and analytical skills. The project focuses on detecting fraudulent transactions, analyzing customer behavior, and generating valuable business insights using structured banking data.
Banks process thousands of financial transactions every day through online banking, ATMs, mobile banking, and branch operations. Monitoring these transactions manually is both time-consuming and inefficient. This project demonstrates how SQL can be used to organize banking data, identify suspicious activities, analyze customer information, and support decision-making through analytical reporting.
The project consists of two relational tables: Customers and Transactions. The Customers table stores customer profile information, while the Transactions table records financial activities such as deposits, withdrawals, and transfers. These tables are connected using Primary Key and Foreign Key relationships, enabling efficient data retrieval and analysis through SQL joins.
The database includes more than 50 sample records for customers and transactions to simulate a realistic banking environment. Various SQL queries are implemented to extract meaningful information, identify fraudulent transactions, classify customers, and produce business reports.
Problem Statement
Banks and financial institutions process millions of transactions daily. Identifying fraudulent transactions among such a large volume of data is a major challenge. Fraudulent activities such as unusually high withdrawals, suspicious fund transfers, repeated transactions, or abnormal customer behavior can result in significant financial losses and security risks.
Traditional manual monitoring is not sufficient to detect fraud efficiently. Therefore, banks rely on data analysis techniques and SQL-based reporting systems to monitor customer activities, identify suspicious transactions, and generate fraud alerts.
This project addresses these challenges by using SQL queries to detect fraud patterns, analyze customer behavior, and produce meaningful business reports.
